## Business Logic

### 1. Summary of the Account Service

The Account Service is designed to manage user accounts through a set of key business processes including account creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion. It ensures that each account has a unique identifier and verifies account existence and status before performing critical operations. The service interacts with both relational and non-relational databases to handle account and bank data. Messaging systems are utilized to publish notifications related to account events, enhancing communication and processing capabilities. The architecture supports a clear flow of data interactions, from client requests through to external service validations, ensuring robust error handling and compliance with business rules. Overall, this service provides a comprehensive solution for managing accounts while maintaining data integrity and operational efficiency.

### 2. Overview Table

| Base Path         | Source Repository                          | Description                                                                                       |
|-------------------|-------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`       | [GitHub Repo Link](#)                    | API for managing user accounts, including creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion operations. |

### 3. Overall API Specification

| Endpoint         | Method | Description                           | Request Body                       | Response Type                   | Authentication |
|------------------|--------|---------------------------------------|------------------------------------|----------------------------------|-----------------|
| /accounts        | GET    | Retrieve all accounts                 | N/A                                | List of Account                  | No              |
| /accounts        | POST   | Create a new account                  | Account object                     | Account object                   | No              |
| /accounts/{id}   | GET    | Retrieve an account by ID             | N/A                                | Account object                   | No              |
| /accounts/{id}   | PUT    | Update an account                     | Account object                     | Account object                   | No              |
| /accounts/{id}   | DELETE | Delete an account                     | N/A                                | No content                       | No              |

### 4. Endpoints Summary

- **GET /accounts**: Retrieves a list of all accounts.
- **POST /accounts**: Creates a new account with the provided details.
- **GET /accounts/{id}**: Retrieves the details of a specific account by its ID.
- **PUT /accounts/{id}**: Updates the details of an existing account identified by its ID.
- **DELETE /accounts/{id}**: Deletes an account identified by its ID. 

This structured presentation encapsulates the core functionalities and operational framework of the Account Service, providing clarity for developers and stakeholders involved in the project.

## Plant UML script

Here's a PlantUML sequence diagram script that captures the key business processes, actors, interactions, and decision points based on the provided business logic. This script includes the necessary components and highlights the interactions between them.

```plantuml
@startuml
actor "Account Holder" as AH
participant "AccountController" as AC
participant "AccountService" as AS
participant "AccountRepository" as AR
participant "BankRepository" as BR
participant "AccountFeignClient" as AFC
participant "KafkaPublisher" as KP
participant "RabbitMQPublisher" as RP
participant "Notification System" as NS
participant "PostgreSQL" as PG
participant "MongoDB" as MG

== Client Request ==
AH -> AC : Request to create a new account\n(Account object)
AC -> AS : createAccount(Account object)

== Account Existence Check ==
AS -> AR : checkAccountExists(Account ID)
alt Account Exists
    AS -> AC : Error: Account already exists\n(BadRequestException)
else Account Does Not Exist
    AS -> AFC : validateAccountStatus(Account ID)
    alt Account Active
        AS -> AR : saveAccount(Account object)
        AR --> AS : Account saved
        AS -> KP : publishAccountCreated(Account object)
        KP --> AS : Message published to Kafka
        AS -> RP : publishAccountCreatedNotification(Account object)
        RP --> AS : Message published to RabbitMQ
        AS -> AC : Response: Account created\n(Account object)
    else Account Inactive
        AS -> AC : Error: Account is inactive\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
    end
end

== Retrieve Account ==
AH -> AC : Request to retrieve account by ID\n(Account ID)
AC -> AS : getAccountById(Account ID)
AS -> AR : findAccountById(Account ID)
alt Account Found
    AS -> AFC : validateAccountStatus(Account ID)
    alt Account Active
        AS -> AC : Response: Account retrieved\n(Account object)
        AS -> KP : publishAccountRetrieved(Account object)
        KP --> AS : Message published to Kafka
    else Account Inactive
        AS -> AC : Error: Account is inactive\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
    end
else Account Not Found
    AS -> AC : Error: Account not found\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
end

== Update Account ==
AH -> AC : Request to update account\n(Account object)
AC -> AS : updateAccount(Account object)
AS -> AR : checkAccountExists(Account ID)
alt Account Exists
    AS -> AFC : validateAccountStatus(Account ID)
    alt Account Active
        AS -> AR : updateAccount(Account object)
        AR --> AS : Account updated
        AS -> KP : publishAccountUpdated(Account object)
        KP --> AS : Message published to Kafka
        AS -> RP : publishAccountUpdatedNotification(Account object)
        RP --> AS : Message published to RabbitMQ
        AS -> AC : Response: Account updated\n(Account object)
    else Account Inactive
        AS -> AC : Error: Account is inactive\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
    end
else Account Does Not Exist
    AS -> AC : Error: Account not found\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
end

== Delete Account ==
AH -> AC : Request to delete account\n(Account ID)
AC -> AS : deleteAccount(Account ID)
AS -> AR : checkAccountExists(Account ID)
alt Account Exists
    AS -> AFC : validateAccountStatus(Account ID)
    alt Account Active
        AS -> AR : deleteAccount(Account ID)
        AR --> AS : Account deleted
        AS -> KP : publishAccountDeleted(Account ID)
        KP --> AS : Message published to Kafka
        AS -> RP : publishAccountDeletedNotification(Account ID)
        RP --> AS : Message published to RabbitMQ
        AS -> AC : Response: Account deleted\n(No content)
    else Account Inactive
        AS -> AC : Error: Account is inactive\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
    end
else Account Does Not Exist
    AS -> AC : Error: Account not found\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
end

@enduml
```

### Explanation of the Diagram:
1. **Actors and Participants**: The diagram includes all key actors such as Account Holder, and the various services and repositories involved in the business logic.
2. **Interactions**: Each interaction is represented with clear messages, showing the flow of requests and responses.
3. **Decision Points**: The diagram highlights critical decision points, such as checking for account existence and validating account status.
4. **Messaging**: It includes the publishing of messages to Kafka and RabbitMQ as per the business logic requirements.
5. **CRUD Operations**: All CRUD operations (Create, Retrieve, Update, Delete) are represented with their respective flows and error handling.

This PlantUML script can be used to generate a sequence diagram that visually represents the described business logic and interactions.

# API Documentation

## /accounts GET
Endpoint URL: /accounts  
HTTP Method: GET  
Authentication: None  
Authorization: None  
Description: Retrieve all accounts.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                     |
|----------------|--------|----------|---------------------------------|
| None           | N/A    | No       | No request parameters required. |

### Sample Request
```json
{}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name     | Type   | Description                     |
|----------------|--------|---------------------------------|
| accounts       | array  | List of account objects.        |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": "1",
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john.doe@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "123456789",
      "accountType": "savings",
      "dateOfBirth": "1990-01-01",
      "bankCode": "XYZ123"
    }
  ]
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountController
- AccountService
- AccountRepository (PostgreSQL)

### Data Mapping
| Source Field    | Target Field                 | Transformation          |
|------------------|-----------------------------|--------------------------|
| account.id       | AccountEntity.id            | Direct mapping           |
| account.name     | AccountEntity.name          | Direct mapping           |
| account.email    | AccountEntity.email         | Direct mapping           |
| account.accountNumber | AccountEntity.accountNumber | Direct mapping       |
| account.accountType | AccountEntity.accountType | Direct mapping           |
| account.dateOfBirth | AccountEntity.dateOfBirth | Direct mapping          |
| account.bankCode | AccountEntity.bankCode      | Direct mapping           |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "No accounts found",
  "code": 404,
  "message": "No accounts exist in the database."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name                   | Description                        | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                |
|------------------------|------------------------------------|----------------|--------|---------------------|----------------------|
| ResourceNotFoundException | Thrown when no accounts are found | N/A            | N/A    | Mandatory            | Indicates absence of data. |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message                  | Description                                   |
|-----------|--------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
| 404       | No accounts found        | No accounts exist in the database.           |
